column2: Sunny- lake down 2" from last week- south wind.
Heavy algae all over lake- no wind.
Cool- sunny- rained 4" during previous week.  Water level: up 4"
Sunny- W wind.  The water color is green but is leans towards brown.
Partly cloudy- rain from 11:00 A.M. to 2:00 P.M.
Little Balsam - lots of algae- sunny- rain- strong wind at 8:00.
Algae in Little Balsam- sunny- no wind.
Clear- sunny day- rained day before.
Lots of rain past few days.
Sunny.  First time Site Two is better than Site One.
Lots of runoff into Little Balsam- water very brown.
Sunny- windy- Little Balsam better than Big Balsam for 1st time.
Water is very brown- 1st time in last 5 years Little Balsam better than Big Balsam Lake.
Water is improving- this is the last reading of the year.
Not good for this time of year.
Best Little Balsam has ever been in last 8 years.
Cloudy- overcast- and the temperature is 78 degrees.
Overcast- partly sunny- and the temperature is 85 degrees.
Sunny and the temperature is 80 degrees.
Sunny and the water is cloudy.
Sunny and the air temperature is 47 degrees.
Partly cloudy- wind clam. Helper: Laura Sloss
Beautiful warm day- no clouds clear sky / wind SSE at 13 mph / barometer 30.12 in Hg / Air Temp 85.0 degrees F.

column1: Lake use light recreational fishing- swimming using boat or pontoon as the platform- some water skiing.
Noted that Snapping and Red Ear Slider (or similar) are coming ashore to lay eggs.  Racoon enjoying the eggs nightly.
Assisting in data collection Faelin Flynn- 6 yrs and Torsten Flynn- 8 yrs.

column2: Clear sky and sunny- southerly winds 8 mph
Partly Cloudy- Winds from the North at 7 mph.  Additional helper was Laura Sloss.
Clear to partly cloudy sky.  Light southwest winds at 7 mph. Air temperature at 74 degrees F.  Helpers: Laura Sloss- Faylin Flynn (3 yrs old) and Torsten Flynn (5 yrs old).
Sky Sunny and blue.  Outside air temperature 80.2 F.  Wind speed and direction: Not recorded.
Blue Sky- Winds speed and direction not recorded.
Partly cloudy with blue sky.  Winds calm. Ambient air temp 78.8 degrees F. Ice out on 04/21/2019

column1: Canadian goose population in Boston Bay and Stumps Bay is significantly down do to a successful 2018 eradication program executed by the Village of Balsam Lake and the Balsam Lake Protection and Rehab district.  Observed one single mature- one young pair with no goslings- one young pair with three healthy goslings.  Bald Eagle sightings appear to be down.  Two young loons sighted. Gold Finches- Barn Swallows- Brown Creepers- Baltimore Orioles- Scarlet Tangager- a pair of Pileated Wood Pecker- Wild Turkey- Red-Bellied Wood Pecker- Mink and a Bull Snake.

column2: Lake level is still relatively high.  Goose population is down by 50%- an acceptable level.  Two tundra swans nesting in Stumps Bay as are a pair of Sandhill Cranes.  It is enjoyable to hear their calls.

column1: Today was clear skies- temp in the low 70's- wind from the East. Water is a little cool but several water skiers and wake boarders.

column2: Clear blue sky- winds out of the West at 10 - 15 mph.  Ambient temp 70.5 degrees Fahrenheit.  Working with Andy Wilhoit.  Grab samples were taken per procedure for phosphorus and Chlorophyll at both sites on Balsam- site 493056 and 493058.  Samples were sent to state lab for analysis.
Clear blue sky- winds out of the West. air temperature 80.4 degrees Fahrenheit.

Clear Blue sky.  Lake. 15 mph wind out of the West.  Haven't heard the geese or the swans in three days.  Saturday night and Sunday experienced substantial rainfall.  The water clarity has deteriorated.  Air Temperature 74.3 degrees F.
Clear blue sky. Wind SSW  at 5mph. Barometric pressure 30.24 in hg. Lake use light moderate tubing and fishing.
Blue Sky - Partly cloudy- SE Wind at 6 mph- Barometric pressure 30.11 in hg- Ambient Air Temperature 76.4 F

column1: Light mixed use today. Mostly recreational boating.

column2: Ambient air temp 87.0 degrees Fahrenheit; Winds ESE at 12 mph; barometric pressure 29.95 in Hg; cloud cover at about 55% - 60%. Light pleasure boating use- swimmers enjoying pleasant water temps to cool off.  Waterfowl includes evening vocalization of Loons- 4 a.m. vocalization of tundra swans before they leave to feeding locations. Have seen several diver ducks in Stumps Bay.  They tend to hang close to shore.  Canadian geese are absent the lake as nuisance control measures have had an impact.  I observed one goose today and have seldom heard any early morning vocalizations.
